<DOC><DOCNO> AP880321-0224 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0819EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv31   03-21 0517</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv 31,0539</SECOND><NOTE>$adv31</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Thursday, March 31</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Thursday, March 31, the 91st day of 1988. There are 275days left in the year.   Today's Highlight in History:   Twenty years ago, on March 31, 1968, President Lyndon B. Johnsonstunned the country with a surprise announcement at the end of abroadcast address on the Vietnam War, telling the audience, ``Ishall not seek, and I will not accept, the nomination of my partyfor another term as your president.''   On this date:   In 1831, Quebec and Montreal were incorporated as cities.   In 1870, Thomas Peterson Mundy cast a ballot in a municipalelection in Perth Amboy, N.J., becoming the first black to votefollowing ratification of the 15th Amendment.   In 1880, Wabash, Ind., became the first town to be completelyilluminated with electrical lighting.   In 1889, the Eiffel Tower, in Paris, was officially opened tothe public.   In 1917, the United States took possession of the Virgin Islandsfrom Denmark.   In 1923, the first dance marathon in the United States, held inNew York City, ended with Alma Cummings setting a world record of27 hours on her feet.   In 1932, Ford Motor Co. publicly unveiled its V-8 engine.   In 1933, during the Great Depression, Congress authorized theCivilian Conservation Corps.   In 1943, the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical ``Oklahoma!''opened on Broadway.   In 1949, Newfoundland entered confederation as Canada's 10thprovince.   In 1953, the United Nations Security Council nominated DagHammarskjold of Sweden to become Secretary-General.   In 1976, the New Jersey Supreme Court ruled that Karen AnneQuinlan, in a coma for almost a year, could be disconnected fromher respirator. Quinlan, who remained in a coma, died in June 1985.   In 1980, former track and field star Jesse Owens, hero of the1936 Berlin Olympics, died in Tucson, Ariz., of lung cancer at theage of 66.   In 1986, 167 people died when a Mexicana Airlines Boeing 727crashed in a remote mountainous region of Mexico in that country'sworst aviation disaster.   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter arrived in Nigeria on thefirst official visit by an American president to black Africa.   Five years ago: Some 5,000 people died when a major earthquakestruck southern Colombia, devastating the mountain city of Popayan.   One year ago: The judge in the ``Baby M'' case in Hackensack,N.J., awarded custody of the girl born under a surrogate-motherhoodcontract to her natural father, William Stern, instead of herbiological mother, Mary Beth Whitehead.   Today's Birthdays: Radio and TV personality Henry Morgan is 73.Actor Richard Kiley is 66. Actor William Daniels is 61. Laborleader Cesar Chavez is 61. Former hockey star Gordie Howe is 60.Actress Shirley Jones is 54. Actor Richard Chamberlain is 53.Musician Herb Alpert is 53. Senator Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., is 48.Actor Christopher Walken is 45. Comedian Gabe Kaplan is 43.   Thought for Today: ``The most important thing about SpaceshipEarth -- an instruction book didn't come with it.'' -- R.Buckminster Fuller, American architect and author (1895-1983).</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv</NOTE></DOC>